{"title_page": "Archeological Site 4-SK-4", "text_new": "{{short description|Prehistoric human settlement  location}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n  | name           = Archeological Site 4-SK-4\n  | image          = Indian Tom Lake Rd.jpeg\n  | caption        = Location of Nightfire Island on a private property adjacent to Otey Ridge in the background\n  | nearest_city   = [[Tulelake, California]]\n  | locmapin       = California#USA\n  | area           = {{convert|2.5|acre}}\n}}\n'''Archeological Site 4-SK-4''', in [[Tulelake, California]], near [[Macdoel, California]], is a stratified [[archeological site]] that was a hunter-gatherer village on the west shores of the [[Lower Klamath Lake]].<ref name=\"ussite\">{{cite web|title=Notice of Inventory Completion: University of Oregon, Oregon State Museum of Anthropology, Eugene, OR|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2009/02/02/E9-2147/notice-of-inventory-completion-university-of-oregon-oregon-state-museum-of-anthropology-eugene-or|accessdate=April 10, 2020 |author=Federal Register, The Daily Journal of the United States Governement||date=February 2, 2009 |}}</ref> The site is located in the heart of the [[Klamath Basin]] wetlands, west of [[Indian Tom Lake]].<ref name=\"site\">{{cite web|last=Garfinkel |first=Alan P. |title=Culture Crisis and Rock Art Intensification:  Numic Ghost Dance Paintings and Coso Representational Petroglyphs |url=http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |accessdate=April 15, 2013 |author2=Geron Marcom |author3=Robert A. Schiffman |date=November 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506092308/http://www.petroglyphs.us/article_culture_crisis_and_rock_art_intensification.htm |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> It has also been known as '''Nightfire Island'''<ref>{{cite book |last= Hughes|first= R E|author-link= |date= 1986|title= Diachronic variability in obsidian procurement patterns in northeastern California and southcentral Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Bvjg2LypUowC|location= |publisher= Univ of California Press|page= |isbn=}}</ref> and as '''Sheepy Island'''.  Prehistorically, it served as a camp on a wetland man-made mound and as a ceremonial site.<ref name=howe>Howe, 8-9</ref> The site shows evidence of human occupancy from the peak of the [[Holocene climatic optimum|Hypsithermal era]], approximately 7,000 years ago.<ref>Johnson, L. (1969). Obsidian hydration rate for the Klamath Basin of California and Oregon. Science, 165(3900), 1354-1356.</ref> [[Obsidian]] [[arrowhead]]s are frequent finds, whose varieties include Northern Sided Notched, [[Elko point|Elko type corner notched]], and Gunther type points.<ref>Justice, N. D. (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC Stone Age spear and arrow points of California and the Great Basin] Indiana University Press. Page 174</ref> \n\nExcavations and sampling started in 1966 by Klamath educator Carrol Howe. The site was described by Garth Sampson in a 1985 publication of the [[University of Oregon]], located in [[Eugene, Oregon]].<ref name=\"geoarch\">{{cite journal|last=Sampson|first=C. Garth|title=Nightfire Island: Later holocene lakemarsh adaptation on the western edge of the great basin|journal=Geoarcheology|year=1985|volume=2|pages=247|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt5wq3p6dd/qt5wq3p6dd.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020|doi=}}</ref> Modern Modocs have called the island ''Shapasheni'' (Shapash /xpni),<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> meaning \"where the sun and moon live\",<ref name=\"Murguia\">{{cite book |last= Murgu\u00eda|first= Alejandro |author-link= |date= 2002|title= The Medicine of Memory: A Mexica Clan in California|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=DVZfAgAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= University of Texas Press|page= 154-155|isbn=0292778708}}</ref> or \"home of the sun and the moon.<ref>{{cite book |last= Doty|first= Thomas |author-link= |date= 2002|title= Doty Meets Coyote|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LhuUCwAAQBAJ|location= |publisher= Blackstone Publishing|page= |isbn=1504708334}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOccupation of the Klamath Basin areas may have begun about 6000 BCE.<ref name=\"geoarch\" /> Settlement by [[Modoc people]] on the banks of Sheepy Creek is likely to have begun approximately 4000 years [[Common Era|BCE]],<ref name=\"grayson\" /> shortly after the eruption of [[Mount Mazama]]. Studies of the archeological site's layers shows that volcanic ash formed a layer on the lake bed just below the layer that marks the appearance of occupation by a new village.<ref name=howe /> \n\nThe shallow water level of the marsh, the clay loam, and the basalt rubble basin extended all around and over this settlement point, meant that the Indian pioneers had to carry rocks to strengthen their foundation. After centuries of this procedure, they had built an island of an area approximately {{Convert|2.5|acre||abbr=}}. Surrounded by marshlands, the villagers could fish and hunt for waterfowl.<ref>Kittredge, W. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U89OpWh0itoC Balancing water: restoring the Klamath Basin]. Univ of California Press. Page 176</ref> The springs that are nearest to Nightfire Island are geothermal waters, adding to the comfort of the villagers. During the dry months, the receding water levels allowed for the establishment of a secure hunting station. Charcoal remains show evidence of cooking pits and cremated burial sites within the island. Bones show an early abundance of duck with additional diversity appearing in later years.<ref name=\"geoarch\" />\n \nFowl droppings on layers in the excavation site show that there were times where the site was abandoned for several hundred years, probably because of the rising of the levels of Indian Tom lake, climate change within the hot and dry middle Holocene, or changes in the Keno fault.<ref name=\"grayson\">Grayson, D. K. (1976). A note on the prehistoric avifauna of the Lower Klamath Basin. The Auk, 93(4), 830-833.</ref> When water levels receded, occupation resumed with the appearance of black charcoal levels from cooking and cremation fires.<ref name=howe />\n\n==Archeology==\nExcavations of archeological site 4-SK-4 have produced large collections of bird, mammal, and fish bones, and large numbers of obsidian technology, particularly Elko points, bone, mortars and other stone artifacts as well as other cultural detritus.<ref name=\"grayson\" /><ref name=\"Murguia\" /> These occupational debris reaches a maximum of 3 meters deep. The lower stratum is [[Lake|lacustrine]], waterway [[diatom]]-rich silt from the original lake floor present during the first occupation of the site. From there, the strata consist of a series of [[silt]], streamland and [[loam]] forming a [[duripan]] horizon.\n\nSamll animals hunted by the villagers were boiled in baskets, larger animals in rock roasting ovens primarily of large basalt rocks. Along with oven rocks, other rocks included broken fragments of [[mortar and pestle]]s and banded stones used for weights. Banded rocks are generally used for outdoor support such as tying down canoes.<ref>{{cite book |last= Carlisle|first= Rodney P. |author-link= |date= 2007|title= Native America from Prehistory to First Contact|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=J7FZggSz3eAC|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page= 177|isbn=1851098291}}</ref> In Nightfire island, banded rocks may have been used for indoor weights since they were found inside the houses and in roasting pits.<ref>Howe, p. 64</ref> The number of these rocks and their weight exceeds the traditional canoe weights and even the weights used by the [[Modoc people]] for the balsa-type rafts. The banded rocks from Nightfire Island show signs of burning mixed with charcoal from cooking fires.<ref>Howe, p. 67</ref> Some stones were used for boiling food in basketry by placing the hot basalt or lava stones into tightly packed woven water-filled baskets.<ref>{{cite book |last= The Library of Native Americans|first= |author-link= |date= 2003|title= The Modoc of California and Oregon|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6AjymTpzRTUC|location= |publisher= The [[Rosen Publishing]] Group|page= 19|isbn=1404226605}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of buffalo hide on Nightfire Island suggest the village hunters used obsidian and [[spear-thrower]]s. The most common arrow point found on the site is the [[Cascade point|Cascade-type]]. Additionally, the excavation has produced several pressure-flaking tools made of bone and antler used for projectiles, especially before the bow and arrow were in use.<ref name=\"Howe72\">Howe, p. 72</ref> Stone anvils from the excavation had single and bilateral worn out pits used for [[knapping]] the obsidian to break the [[spall]]s from the rock.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hranicky|first= Wm Jack |author-link= |date= 2013|title= Archaeological Concepts, Techniques, and Terminology for American Prehistoric Lithic Technology|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PSDtkmsHIEsC|location= |publisher= AuthorHouse|page=82, 277 |isbn=1481751743}}</ref> The large amount of anvils found on Nightfire Island suggest they were used for other purposes than knapping, including cracking bones. The side pits are not worn out consistent with the use as a maul or pounding food.<ref name=\"Howe72\" /> \n\nWhile Modocs of the [[Great Basin]] had chipped-stone crescents or lunates,<ref>{{cite book |last= Justice|first= Noel D. |date= 2002|title= Stone Age Spear and Arrow Points of California and the Great Basin|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kzrfXiifiToC|location= |publisher= Indiana University Press|page=116|isbn=0253108837}}</ref><ref>University of California Archaeological Survey, & Berkeley. Archaeological Research Facility. (1960). [https://books.google.com/books?id=0rKVdi0HrusC Reports of the University of California Archaeological Survey]. University of California Archaeological Survey, Department of Anthropology, University of California. p. 44.</ref> their presence has not been confirmed on Nightfire Island. Some smaller versions have been excavated but they are of a different shape and material.<ref name=\"Howe33\">Howe, p. 33 </ref> \n\n===Culture===\nExcavations have unearthed structures that suggest buildings similar to [[sweat lodge]]s in Nightfire Island. Carbon-14 dated to approximately 1,500 years ago, these would be the oldest remains of a sweat lodge.<ref name=\"Murguia\" />\n\nA higher than usual frequency of neuronal malformations discovered within Nightfire Island suggested tentatively that inbreeding might be in part responsible.<ref>Bennett, K. A. (1972). [https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ajpa.1330360315 Lumbo\u2010sacral malformations and spina bifida occulta in a group of proto\u2010historic Modoc Indians]. ''American Journal of Physical Anthropology'', 36(3), 435-439.</ref> Studies of skeletal remains also revealed an unusually large and deep fossae lateral in the 1st and 2nd sacral tuberosities, suggesting a very strong postural ligament attachment.<ref>de la Mata, R. C., & Bonavia, D. (1980). [https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/202506?journalCode=ca Lumbosacral malformations and spina bifida in a Peruvian preceramic child]. ''Current Anthropology'', 21(4), 515-516.</ref>\n\n===Paleontology finds===\n\n*'''Aves:''' , ''[[Podiceps]]'' spp., ''[[Cygnus (genus)|Cygnus]]'' spp., ''[[Branta]]'' spp., ''[[Anas]]'' spp., ''[[Aythya]]'' spp., ''[[Bucephala (bird)|Bucephala]]'' spp., ''[[Mergus]]'' spp.\n\nThe bird life of Nightfire island includes the following species dated by radiocarbon determinations:<ref name=\"grayson\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Dates and species defined by number of identified specimens\n|-\n!from 4000-3000 BC\n!from 3000-2200 BC\n!from 2020 BC-AD 0\n!from 0-1400 AD\n|-\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (0)\n|[[Common loon]] (5)\n|[[Common loon]] (17)\n|-\n|[[Horned grebe]] (0)\n|[[Horned grebe]] (1)\n|[[