e=\"col\" | First edition publisher<br />\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Eastward Ho''\n| 1919\n|\n| Musical comedy, written with [[Oscar Asche]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref name =\"SmithersAppx\" />\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{OL_author|OL6962599A|Dornford Yates}}\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Yates,+Dornford | name=Dornford Yates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, Dornford}}\n[[Category:Bibliographies by writer]]\n[[Category:Bibliographies of British writers]]\n[[Category:Dornford Yates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Works by the English novelist Cecil William Mercer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Cecil William Mercer\n| image =Dornford Yates (Cecil William Mercer) by George Charles Beresford (1909).jpg\n| caption=Cecil William Mercer in 1909\n| pseudonym = Dornford Yates\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1885|8|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Walmer]], Kent\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1960|3|5|1885|8|7|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Umtali]], [[Southern Rhodesia]]\n| occupation = Author\n| nationality = English\n| alma_mater =[[University College, Oxford]]\n| genre =\n| notableworks =\n}}\n\n'''[[Dornford Yates]]''' was the pseudonym of the English novelist '''Cecil William Mercer''' (7 August 1885 \u2013 5 March 1960), whose novels and short stories, some humorous (the ''Berry'' books), some [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]s (the ''Chandos'' books), were best-sellers in the period between the First and Second World Wars.\n\nThe categorization of Yates's novels is based on the list that appears opposite the title page of his last published work, ''B-Berry And I Look Back''.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Yates |first=Dornford |title=''B-Berry And I Look Back'' |publisher=[[Ward Lock & Co]] |year=1958 |at=Opposite title page}}</ref> All works are full-length novels except where noted. Not included are the uncollected short stories.\n{{clear}}\n\n== The Berry books ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+\nThe Berry Books\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year of first<br />publication\n! scope=\"col\" | First edition publisher<br />\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''The Brother of Daphne''\n| 1914\n|[[Ward Lock & Co]]\n| Short stories, originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]''<ref name =\"SmithersAppx\">{{Cite book|at=Appendix I |title=Dornford Yates |last= Smithers |first=AJ |publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton|Hodder and Stoughton]] |year=1982 |location=London |isbn=0 340 27547 2}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref name=\"BLcat003995523\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995523&con_lng=eng |title=British Library details for item 003995523  |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''The Courts of Idleness''\n| 1920\n|[[Ward Lock & Co]]\n|Short stories, originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref name=\"BLcat003995525\">{{Cite web|url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995525&con_lng=eng|title=British Library details for item 003995525&nbsp;|website=primocat.bl.uk|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Berry and Co.''\n| 1921\n|[[Ward Lock & Co]]\n|Short stories, originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref name=\"BLcat0039955172\">{{Cite web|url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995517&con_lng=eng|title=British Library details for item 003995517|website=primocat.bl.uk|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\